For $A\in\mathbb{R}^{n,n}$, $p(x)=\det(A-xI)$ has degree $n$ and:
- its **real roots are exactly the eigenvalues** of $A$;
- $p(0)=\det A$ (constant term);
- the leading term is $(-1)^n x^n$;
- the coefficient of $x^{n-1}$ is $(-1)^{n-1}\operatorname{tr}A$ (sum of diagonal entries).
For a $2\times2$ matrix $\begin{pmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{pmatrix}$ this gives $p(x)=x^2-(a+d)x+(ad-bc)$.
